INSERT INTO message (id, channelId, userId, message, createdAt, updatedAt) VALUES ('1187283011247550485', '1178822630225227818', '139462049976549377', 'I found an article *written by Slack* that says they store their messages in MySQL https://slack.engineering/scaling-datastores-at-slack-with-vitess/. They just have some intense sharding to get it to scale properly.\n\nThis was my bad, because when I researched last month I read an article from a third party that said they store messages in DynamoDB, but that seems to be innaccurate.\n\nHowever, since they encrypt the ""plaintext"" of the data in the database and rely on search indexes to search through the ""encrypted data"" then we a good moat since raw SQL access would be useless if they encrypt this stuff. And you can''t run MySQL on memory so you can''t do that funky stuff we are doing. And they encrypt IDs... which like... wtf are you going to do at that point loll\n\nAdditionally, MySQL doesn''t have RLS which means they **have** to have their security layer tied to the API, so I doubt even if they wanted to, no security person there would ever give raw SQL access **especially** because they have a multi-tenant database architecture, which means they store multiple tenants (orgs) on teh same database.\n\nOverall we have a massive moat still with SQLite. I think it will be actually impossible for them to give raw SQL access, especially with the ""conservative"" decision making they keep bringing up in every article I''ve read from their engineering field.', 1703140728533, 1703140728533);
